rdf:Description.lla:note: Joseph Edlin joined purporting to be a competent cook, but, according to the captain, turned out to never have performed such duties before and was "wholly incompetent". The other men complained that they could not berth with him in the fo'castle as he was too filthy. He was examined and found to be entirely verminous. He was given soap to wash himself and the carpenter made up a separate berth for him on the after deck. At Bari he complained about illness and could not unload cargo. He was taken to the hospital and housed in the courtyard as his disease was venereal. Two weeks later he returned to the vessel in much better condition. The captain paid 33 Francs for his medicine, to be deducted from wages. He was eventually discharged through sickness in Constantinople.
Discharged 'before the counsul by mutual consent'. See Log book. Date of discharge is recorded as 11/06/1867 in the Official Log.

James Langan is reported in the captain's log as swearing and cursing awfully. According to the log he said that, "he would not die happy before he would have the chance to maltreat the damn son of a bitch of a master". At Bari he got drunk and would not work the following day. When challenged about his work he became aggressive. He said, "that he was a true born American although his name being on the ship's articles as been born in Dublin, and he would be damned if he would wipe his backside with the English Flag". According to the captain, he is "always the instigator of all disagreableness on board". The captain also asserted that he was one of the most nervous men aloft that he had ever seen. Frances Jose Vila complained that Langan had stolen his sugar, tobacco and matches. Langan wished to fight Vila who would not. Vila complained that he would leave the ship as he could, "not get quietness from the American either night or day". Eventually Langan was brought before the consul at Constantinople and sentenced to one month's imprisonment because of his conduct.
